  "body": "#### System information\r\n```\r\n$ geth version\r\nGeth\r\nVersion: 1.9.14-unstable\r\nGit Commit: 5c3993444d725aba00c7c8c976c5cc9f4bf6a317\r\nGit Commit Date: 20200427\r\nArchitecture: amd64\r\nProtocol Versions: [65 64 63]\r\nGo Version: go1.13.7\r\nOperating System: darwin\r\nGOPATH=\r\nGOROOT=/usr/local/go\r\n```\r\n\r\n#### Expected behaviour\r\n`eth_sign` returns the same signatures when using standard account management and clef account management.  The returned signatures can be used to recover the address with `personal_ecRecover`.\r\n\r\n#### Actual behaviour\r\nDifferent signatures are returned when calling `eth_sign` with and without clef.  When running geth with `--signer`, attempting `personal_ecRecover` with the returned signature fails with error `invalid Ethereum signature (V is not 27 or 28)`\r\n\r\n#### Steps to reproduce the behaviour\r\n1. Start clef\r\n1. Start geth with `--signer /path/to/clef.ipc`\r\n1. Attach to js console\r\n1. Call `eth.sign(...)`\r\n1. Compare result to that returned when geth is started without `--signer`\r\n\r\n#### Cause\r\nWhen using clef as geth's signer, the `v` value of the signature is being incremented by `27`  twice (so that it ends up being `54/55`):\r\n1. By clef's `account_signData` method: https://github.com/ethereum/go-ethereum/blob/master/signer/core/signed_data.go#L157 \r\n1. By Geth's `eth_sign` method: https://github.com/ethereum/go-ethereum/blob/master/internal/ethapi/api.go#L1584\r\n",
